In .NET MAUI, those `Application`-level overrides are replaced by **`Window` lifecycle events**. You create a custom `Window` subclass and override the corresponding methods:

| Xamarin.Forms | .NET MAUI (`Window`) |
|---------------|----------------------|
| `OnStart()`   | `OnCreated()`        |
| `OnSleep()`   | `OnStopped()`        |
| `OnResume()`  | `OnResumed()`        |

**Example:**

```csharp
// MyWindow.cs
public class MyWindow : Window
{
    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnCreated()
    {
        base.OnCreated();
        // formerly OnStart
    }

    protected override void OnStopped()
    {
        base.OnStopped();
        // formerly OnSleep
    }

    protected override void OnResumed()
    {
        base.OnResumed();
        // formerly OnResume
    }
}
```

Then wire it up in your `App` class:

```csharp
// App.xaml.cs
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    {
        return new MyWindow(new MainPage());
    }
}
```

There are also additional window events available in MAUI that didn't exist in Xamarin.Forms: `OnActivated()`, `OnDeactivated()`, `OnDestroying()`, and `OnBackgrounding()`.
